WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.110 --> 00:00:09.890
PROFESSOR: --questions about
what we've done.

00:00:09.890 --> 00:00:13.460
I think it's been fast, but
hopefully if you understand

00:00:13.460 --> 00:00:16.500
the principles, we didn't
go too fast.

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:19.190
But any questions on
what we've done?

00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:25.720
I guess you haven't had
a chance to think

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:27.980
of questions yet.

00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:33.240
Let me take care of our oddball
symmetry at the end of

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:38.150
the chart that I handed
out-- and this 4 bar--

00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:42.110
and ask what we can do there.

00:00:42.110 --> 00:00:50.060
Having discovered the four bar
operation in 2, 2, 2 with

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:53.960
diagonal mirror planes, we can
consider that as a new type of

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:55.650
symmetry element.

00:00:55.650 --> 00:01:02.450
And this is the symbol for it.

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:07.430
And this would take a pair of
objects and repeat them by a

00:01:07.430 --> 00:01:09.440
180 degree rotation.

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:13.640
And then another pair of
opposite handedness, opposite

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:18.980
chirality would be rotated 90
degrees and inverted, rotated

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:21.210
90 degrees and inverted.

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:29.110
And I mentioned last time that a
solid that has this shape is

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:31.130
something called a sphenoid.

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:39.580
And the 4 bar axis takes a pair
of faces that are up and

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:43.940
a pair of faces that are down
and skewed by 90 degrees.

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:45.890
Now what can we do?

00:01:45.890 --> 00:01:52.780
If we add a mirror plane that's
perpendicular to the 4

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:55.850
bar axis, the right-handed
one goes down, the

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:57.480
left-handed one comes up.

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:03.200
And it becomes simply 4 over
m, which we've already got.

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:08.725
If we add a vertical mirror
plane through the 4 bar, if

00:02:08.725 --> 00:02:18.040
you look a bit earlier at 4 bar
2m, now we've got the 4

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:21.420
bar, now we've got
the mirror plane.

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:26.070
Not surprisingly, we get
the two mirror planes.

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:41.200
And so S4v is going to be
the same as 4 bar 2m.

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.400
And that's something we
already have D2d.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.030
So that exhausts the
possibilities.

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:51.595
4 bar just stands by itself.

00:02:55.220 --> 00:02:58.790
At a vertical mirror plane,
it's D2d 4 bar 2m.

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:01.920
At a horizontal mirror plane,
it becomes 4 over m.

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:08.300
The diagonal mirror plane
is not possible.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:11.500
There's nothing to place the
mirror plane diagonal to.

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:14.290
And if you add inversion, it
changes into 4 over m.

00:03:14.290 --> 00:03:16.100
So this one is an odd group.

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:19.330
It sits by itself.

00:03:19.330 --> 00:03:21.860
Except that we could start
there, and add a vertical

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:27.070
mirror plane, and get
4 bar 2m once more.

00:03:27.070 --> 00:03:31.160
That leaves the cubic ones,
which are really easy to deal

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.490
with because a cube has
such high symmetry.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:35.450
We all know what cubes
look like.

00:03:35.450 --> 00:03:39.210
But when you show arrangements
of motifs, it gets a little

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:41.070
bit confusing.

00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:44.295
So let's take a look at the
tetrahedral groups.

00:03:47.630 --> 00:03:53.360
T is a combination of twofold
axes coming out in directions

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:55.670
corresponding to face
normals to a cube.

00:04:00.590 --> 00:04:02.865
So these are the twofold axes.

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:14.140
And then there are threefold
axes coming out of directions

00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:17.760
that correspond to the
face diagonal.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:22.060
So this is the jack-o'-lantern
stereographic projection,

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:27.410
which is something I love to
draw at this time of year.

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:29.360
What will the pattern
look like?

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.760
Well, it's going to
look like 2, 2, 2.

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:38.200
So that's a subgroup.

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:42.050
So let's draw in a pair of
objects on either side of the

00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:45.774
twofold axis, and that's
the pattern of 2, 2, 2.

00:04:45.774 --> 00:04:50.420
Now this guy here is lurking
off of a threefold axis.

00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:54.570
So that threefold axis is
going to repeat it three

00:04:54.570 --> 00:04:58.800
locations that are 120
degrees apart.

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:03.700
And so there's going to be a
triangle of objects up above.

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:10.660
This threefold axis is going
to reproduce this into a

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:13.660
triangle of objects that
are down below.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:17.100
The twofold axis will take this
triangle of objects and

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:19.390
move it over to here.

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:21.090
Also, up.

00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:24.110
And the twofold axis that's
vertical will take this

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:29.450
triangle and move it down
to three that are below.

00:05:29.450 --> 00:05:31.540
So it looks very complicated
in projection.

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:35.700
But it's simply a planar
triangle of atoms here rotated

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:36.740
180 degrees.

00:05:36.740 --> 00:05:38.330
So you've got one like
this, one like this.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:41.925
And then down below, two other
planar triangles of objects.

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:58.050
Remembering what the symmetry
of a tetrahedron looks like,

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:04.150
you can draw this arrangement of
symmetry elements relative

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:06.510
to a tetrahedron.

00:06:06.510 --> 00:06:09.890
And the threefold axes
now are coming out

00:06:09.890 --> 00:06:11.365
normal to the faces.

00:06:11.365 --> 00:06:14.160
The twofold axes coming out
normal to the edges.

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:20.800
And imagine that we put a
triangle on this face, a

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:24.700
similar triangle on the face
behind, and a triangle

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:27.300
pointing in the other direction
down this way.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:28.830
These are the three below.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.960
So that's the pattern of 2, 3.

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:35.400
Take a tetrahedron, smack a
triangle on the two upper

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:39.130
faces, and an equilateral
triangle on

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:41.590
the two lower faces.

00:06:41.590 --> 00:06:44.880
And the threefold axis that
comes out here comes out of

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:47.000
the center of this triangle
and out of the

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:48.250
center of this triangle.

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:06.230
The next one that you can
get from this is Th, the

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:08.530
tetrahedral arrangement
of axes with a

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:11.470
horizontal mirror plane.

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:14.290
If you put in a horizontal
mirror plane, it's going to

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:19.850
take this triangle and
reflect it down.

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:22.540
It's going to take this triangle
and reflect it up.

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:26.336
And they will overlap
in projection.

00:07:26.336 --> 00:07:30.440
And so that's the
pattern for Th.

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:32.470
There's a mirror plane
perpendicular

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:34.880
to a twofold axis.

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:36.920
That creates an inversion
center.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.200
So we can call this
a 3 bar axis.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:44.360
So that's Th 2 over m 3 bar.

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:56.715
So just have triangles on the
upper and lower faces as well.

00:08:03.270 --> 00:08:11.970
The one remaining one is Td.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:19.850
Here are the twofold axes.

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:24.620
Here are the threefold axes.

00:08:24.620 --> 00:08:28.780
And now if we put a diagonal
mirror plane in, diagonal with

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:29.690
respect to what?

00:08:29.690 --> 00:08:32.390
Well, diagonal with respect
to these twofold axes.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:37.140
So this mirror plane goes down
like this, passes through a

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:38.110
twofold axis.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:42.799
There must be a mirror plane
90 degrees away.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:50.170
And the threefold axis is going
to repeat these mirror

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:58.270
planes so that we get mirror
planes that are at an angle

00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:01.210
with respect to the vertical
twofold axis.

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:05.100
And this is Td.

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:10.800
And this, in the international
notation, is called-- if we

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:12.320
can figure it out--

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:16.470
the diagonal mirror planes with
respect to these twofold

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:20.250
axes have changed them
into 4 bar axes.

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:26.740
So this is called 4 bar
3m, which doesn't

00:09:26.740 --> 00:09:28.230
look cubic at all.

00:09:28.230 --> 00:09:29.555
So that's a little
bit deceptive.

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:41.960
I am foolhardy for even
trying to do this.

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:44.280
And so I don't think
I'm going to do it.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:50.930
4, 3, 2, we know what
that looks like.

00:09:50.930 --> 00:09:53.930
That is fourfold axes coming
out in directions that

00:09:53.930 --> 00:10:01.115
correspond to the face
normals to a cube.

00:10:01.115 --> 00:10:06.110
A threefold axis coming
out of body diagonals.

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:09.460
Twofold axes between all of
the fourfold axes that are

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:11.170
normal to the edges
of the cube.

00:10:13.910 --> 00:10:17.830
So all sorts of rotational
symmetry.

00:10:17.830 --> 00:10:24.020
That, if you want a pattern, has
a triangle that's on about

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:28.600
each of the threefold axes.

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:33.970
But the one that is up, points
in the opposite orientation of

00:10:33.970 --> 00:10:37.760
the one that's on the threefold
axis coming out of

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:38.860
the other end of the cube.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:42.280
So you have one triangle
that's like this, up.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:45.810
And another triangle like this
that's on the other end of the

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:48.570
threefold axis that points
down into the blackboard.

00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:57.440
What can you add as
other extenders?

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:00.890
You can put in a mirror plane
that is perpendicular to the

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:02.480
fourfold axis.

00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:04.973
And that leaves everything
unchanged.

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:12.720
Now we've got a mirror plane
passing through a fourfold

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:15.370
axis, so we have to
have mirror planes

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:18.420
at 45 degree intervals.

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:21.650
And that will create mirror
planes there.

00:11:21.650 --> 00:11:24.050
This horizontal mirror plane
goes through this fourfold

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:28.370
axis, so there must be mirror
planes at 45 degree intervals.

00:11:28.370 --> 00:11:30.040
So there's another one
like this and 90

00:11:30.040 --> 00:11:31.930
degrees away as well.

00:11:31.930 --> 00:11:34.680
The fourfold axis is
perpendicular to a mirror

00:11:34.680 --> 00:11:37.650
plane, as are these other
twofold axes, so there's an

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:39.140
inversion center.

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:42.600
Here's a fourfold axis with a
vertical mirror plane going

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:42.930
through it.

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:45.885
And it has to have a vertical
mirror plane going like this

00:11:45.885 --> 00:11:47.090
at 45 degrees away.

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:48.400
So that's the symmetry.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:52.910
This is the regular symmetry
of a cube or an octahedron.

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.880
And I will not, even if
pressured, try to draw a

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:59.870
pattern that conforms to that.

00:11:59.870 --> 00:12:01.990
We've got the fourfold axis

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:04.990
perpendicular to a mirror plane.

00:12:04.990 --> 00:12:07.820
And this is called
O sub h, O with a

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:11.030
horizontal mirror plane.

00:12:11.030 --> 00:12:17.590
The fourfold axis in 4, 3,
2 has got a mirror plane

00:12:17.590 --> 00:12:18.670
perpendicular to it.

00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:20.860
The twofold axes all pick
up mirror planes

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:22.230
perpendicular to them.

00:12:22.230 --> 00:12:25.270
There's an inversion center at
the point of intersection.

00:12:25.270 --> 00:12:28.520
So we label this axis
a 3 bar axis.

00:12:28.520 --> 00:12:32.840
So that's O sub h, 4 over
m, 3 bar, 2 over m.

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:37.655
And this, as I say, is the
symmetry of a regular cube or

00:12:37.655 --> 00:12:40.280
an octahedron.

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:41.580
Nothing else we can do here.

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:44.730
There's so many symmetry axes
all over the place that

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:48.730
there's no way we can snake in
any diagonal mirror plane.

00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:53.070
Because there is no second axis
of the same kind adjacent

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:55.360
to either the twofold,
the threefold, or

00:12:55.360 --> 00:12:56.400
the fourfold axis.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:59.230
So we can't put a mirror plane
in here between the threefold

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:00.680
and the twofold.

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:03.245
We can't put a mirror plane in
here between the fourfold and

00:13:03.245 --> 00:13:04.130
the twofold.

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:05.060
So we're done.

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:09.250
And this is the final and
30 second combination.

00:13:09.250 --> 00:13:14.082
So there are 32 crystallographic
point groups.

00:13:14.082 --> 00:13:14.570
AUDIENCE: Professor?

00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:15.280
PROFESSOR: Yes, sir.

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:22.084
AUDIENCE: So if m3m is a regular
operation, are there

00:13:22.084 --> 00:13:23.334
symbols [INAUDIBLE]?

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:29.190
PROFESSOR: O is the symbol
for 4, 3, 2.

00:13:29.190 --> 00:13:32.690
And what we added as an extender
is a mirror plane

00:13:32.690 --> 00:13:34.550
perpendicular to the
fourfold axis.

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:38.000
That is just one way of
adding an extender.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.800
This is also Oi.

00:13:39.800 --> 00:13:42.690
If we add an inversion center,
we get all this.

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:46.090
And if you look at the ones
have been honored by being

00:13:46.090 --> 00:13:51.250
designated by a symbol, the
horizontal mirror plane takes

00:13:51.250 --> 00:13:53.230
the precedence.

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:57.510
So for example, for 2 over m, 2
over m, 2 over m, you've got

00:13:57.510 --> 00:13:59.930
two different vertical mirror
planes, and you've got one

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:01.360
horizontal mirror plane.

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:04.820
But it's called 2 over m,
2 over m, 2 over m.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:07.670
You can call it 2,
2, 2, m, m, m.

00:14:07.670 --> 00:14:12.050
That's also a possible symbol,
but much more of a mouthful.

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:15.720
There's some arbitrariness
to the symbol because the

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:18.900
arrangement of symmetry elements
is what's real.

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:22.180
And we decide how we
want to devise a

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:24.730
notation to label them.

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:27.660
And as we've seen, there are
two different people who

00:14:27.660 --> 00:14:30.690
adopted a different code
for giving them names.

00:14:30.690 --> 00:14:32.870
So if it's rational and

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:38.610
informative, it's a good notation.

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:41.650
Interestingly, the international
notation, on the

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:44.520
one hand, and the Schoenflies
notation, on the other,

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:46.090
complimentary.

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:48.280
The international notation
tells you

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:51.260
unambiguously what you have.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:56.310
So 2, 2, 2 over m, m, m tells
you three orthogonal twofold

00:14:56.310 --> 00:14:58.400
axes if you remember what
came out of [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:58.400 --> 00:14:59.320
construction.

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:02.480
And perpendicular to each of
them is a mirror plane.

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:04.170
And that's what you've got.

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:07.590
Schoenflies tells you
how you derived it.

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:13.120
You took D2, and that's the
dihedral group 2, 2, 2, and

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:16.340
you added an h, a horizontal
mirror plane.

00:15:16.340 --> 00:15:17.490
And all hell broke loose.

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:19.130
And you got mirror planes
perpendicular to all the

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:20.320
twofold axes.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:22.950
So there's a certain
complementarity to the two

00:15:22.950 --> 00:15:24.950
different notations.

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:29.870
And the people who do
diffraction and

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:34.760
crystallography for the most
part follow the international

00:15:34.760 --> 00:15:37.520
notation, the Hermann-Mauguin
notation.

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:40.810
The people who do condensed
matter physics use the

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:42.340
Schoenflies notation.

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:45.490
Because it's more inscrutable.

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:47.670
And condensed matter physicists
like to be

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:52.190
inscrutable because it's
how you gain respect.

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:58.080
So both notation survive, but
are more prevalent in some

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:00.930
disciplines than in others
and vice versa.

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:11.590
Let's take a brief look ahead.

00:16:11.590 --> 00:16:13.610
What remains to be done?

00:16:13.610 --> 00:16:18.465
We now have the 32
crystallographic point groups.

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:25.410
These are the way things can be
arranged by symmetry about

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:28.420
a fixed point in space.

00:16:28.420 --> 00:16:31.230
If we were to proceed in the
same way that we did for the

00:16:31.230 --> 00:16:34.620
two-dimensional space groups,
what we should do next is

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:38.960
decide what sort of
three-dimensional space

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:42.760
lattices these symmetries
will require.

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:49.110
And then proceed to drop each of
the point groups into each

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:52.660
of the lattices that can
accommodate them.

00:16:52.660 --> 00:16:56.060
And then use the tricks that
we've used in two dimensions,

00:16:56.060 --> 00:16:59.920
take mirror planes and replace
them by glide planes.

00:16:59.920 --> 00:17:03.130
And then having done that, we
would take the mirror planes

00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:08.160
and the rotation axes
and interweave them.

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:12.060
And lest that job seem too
daunting, let me point out

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:15.760
that we already have 17
of the space groups.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:19.089
All we have to do is take
the plane groups, take a

00:17:19.089 --> 00:17:21.579
translation that's perpendicular
to the plane of

00:17:21.579 --> 00:17:24.914
the plane group, and let all the
rotation axes and mirror

00:17:24.914 --> 00:17:28.054
planes extend up indefinitely
in three dimensions parallel

00:17:28.054 --> 00:17:30.600
to that translation.

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:33.740
So we already have 17 of the

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:35.360
three-dimensional space groups.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:39.430
They look just like the plane
groups except they extend in a

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:43.020
direction that's perpendicular
to the plane of our original

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:45.030
two-dimensional group.

00:17:45.030 --> 00:17:48.260
So we're already a long
way towards deriving a

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:52.020
three-dimensional space group
without really knowing it.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:55.130
But what I would like to
consider next is the lattices

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:57.870
that are required for
three dimensions.

00:17:57.870 --> 00:18:02.160
And I've already given you how
one can approach this problem.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:07.360
Take the lattices that have
been required in the

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:09.190
two-dimensional plane groups.

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:13.280
And if the presence of a
threefold axis and the base of

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:19.510
the cell require, say, net
that is hexagonal with a1

00:18:19.510 --> 00:18:29.160
equal to a2 identically in
magnitude and exactly at 120

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:30.945
degrees with respect
to one another.

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:39.770
Let's let the third translation
be perpendicular

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:42.170
to the base.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:44.430
If it's hexagonal, we have
to have at least a

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:47.690
threefold axis here.

00:18:47.690 --> 00:18:51.270
And we've found that adding a
threefold axis to that net

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:53.830
gave rise to two other threefold
axes in the center

00:18:53.830 --> 00:18:55.200
of the triangle.

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:59.740
So one lattice would be one in
which the third translation,

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:03.850
which we'll label c,
is straight up.

00:19:08.530 --> 00:19:11.670
In other words, perpendicular to
the net that we derived in

00:19:11.670 --> 00:19:14.010
two dimensions.

00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:17.320
What we will have as a
constraint is that if we pick

00:19:17.320 --> 00:19:21.180
a certain translation that is
not normal to the plane group,

00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:25.080
and let's say it terminates
here in projection.

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:28.130
So the third translation
goes up and over.

00:19:28.130 --> 00:19:31.380
If there's a threefold axis at
this end of the translation,

00:19:31.380 --> 00:19:34.010
there must be a threefold
axis at the end of that

00:19:34.010 --> 00:19:35.280
translation.

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:39.200
And that mucks everything up,
and we no longer have a group.

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:41.880
We can't have another threefold
axis poking down

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:45.520
through the plane of this
two-dimensional plane group.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:50.300
But it is perfectly OK if the
third translation moves this

00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:53.830
threefold axis and puts down
a lattice point and another

00:19:53.830 --> 00:19:57.590
threefold axis directly
over this one.

00:19:57.590 --> 00:20:00.270
Or alternatively, another
choice for T3

00:20:00.270 --> 00:20:01.580
would be this one.

00:20:01.580 --> 00:20:04.980
That would put the lattice
point in a threefold axis

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:06.120
directly over this one.

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:09.790
So again, we have threefold axes
extending normal to the

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:11.123
plane of my drawing.

00:20:11.123 --> 00:20:14.370
And I've created no
threefold axes.

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:19.220
So with a threefold axis, there
are three potentially

00:20:19.220 --> 00:20:23.770
different space lattices, one in
which the third translation

00:20:23.770 --> 00:20:26.760
is normal to the plane of the
plane group, another one where

00:20:26.760 --> 00:20:28.900
the translation terminates
over the

00:20:28.900 --> 00:20:31.200
other two twofold axes.

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:33.290
And so this is the way in which
one would proceed to

00:20:33.290 --> 00:20:36.950
derive the space lattices.

00:20:36.950 --> 00:20:38.710
Buerger does not
do it this way.

00:20:38.710 --> 00:20:40.180
He doesn't look at
the plane groups.

00:20:40.180 --> 00:20:45.150
He looks just at where the
axes sit in the nets.

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:47.150
No mirror planes whatsoever.

00:20:47.150 --> 00:20:48.610
And I'll return to the point.

00:20:48.610 --> 00:20:52.490
And the place where I think he's
wrong is that if you add

00:20:52.490 --> 00:21:00.410
a twofold axis to a centered
net, you get twofold axes in

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:04.131
all of these locations.

00:21:04.131 --> 00:21:06.620
These are the twofold
axes in C2mm.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.970
And if that's all you look at,
there's no reason why this

00:21:13.970 --> 00:21:17.100
should be the plane group.

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:20.800
And it looks as though you can
make T3 terminate over this

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:22.220
twofold axis.

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:25.710
And that would give you a
peculiar triple cell with

00:21:25.710 --> 00:21:28.680
three lattice points along
the long diagonal of

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:31.720
a rectangular net.

00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:35.490
And you say, wow, 15
space lattices.

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:38.970
We're going to be famous,
if not rich.

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:43.620
You can't do that because this
plane group can exist only if

00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:46.330
there are mirror planes
in here like this.

00:21:46.330 --> 00:21:50.590
And then through these twofold
axes, these have to be glides.

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:54.820
So you can't take 2mm and
put it on top of 2gg.

00:21:54.820 --> 00:21:56.830
It's impossible.

00:21:56.830 --> 00:22:00.050
So there are 14 space
lattices.

00:22:00.050 --> 00:22:01.500
The 15th doesn't exist.

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:04.000
But it looks as though it's
possible in Buerger's

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.040
treatment when he looks just
at the placement of the

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:09.180
rotation axes alone and not
the location of any mirror

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:13.040
planes that are in
the plane groups.

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:16.010
So that is where we're
going to go next.

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:19.000
And that is a process
that actually is

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.670
surprisingly simple.

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:25.120
And we will get the space
lattices very quickly.

00:22:25.120 --> 00:22:27.430
We'll get a number of space
groups along the way,

00:22:27.430 --> 00:22:28.740
as we've just seen.

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:32.100
And then we will cut to the
bottom line and just look at

00:22:32.100 --> 00:22:36.700
how this information is
tabulated in tables for you in

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:39.230
a fashion that's analogous to
the representation of the

00:22:39.230 --> 00:22:40.420
plane groups.

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:41.260
So we're pretty close.

00:22:41.260 --> 00:22:44.325
We'll be wrapping things up in
another two or three meetings.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:50.590
What I would like to do in the
time that remains though, the

00:22:50.590 --> 00:22:54.496
point groups are very difficult
to visualize unless

00:22:54.496 --> 00:22:59.130
you look at real crystals.

00:22:59.130 --> 00:23:03.640
So what I'm going to do is pass
around a collection of

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:05.360
models of actual crystals.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:09.870
I'm not sure I can tell you what
every one of these models

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:11.120
represents.

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:12.740
These are curious things.

00:23:12.740 --> 00:23:15.980
I would beg you not to
drop them on one

00:23:15.980 --> 00:23:19.030
of the sharp corners.

00:23:19.030 --> 00:23:20.210
These are made out of wood.

00:23:20.210 --> 00:23:25.200
They're made out of pear wood in
the Black Forest by elves.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:28.230
No, that last part
is not true.

00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:30.700
But they are incredibly
expensive.

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:32.880
Because the angles in
these things have

00:23:32.880 --> 00:23:34.780
to be exactly right.

00:23:34.780 --> 00:23:38.140
So they are made on the same
sort of machine that you use

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:40.480
for faceting diamonds.

00:23:40.480 --> 00:23:43.380
It's something that has two
degrees of freedom, so you can

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:47.220
get a surface that you want on
the material exactly parallel

00:23:47.220 --> 00:23:48.690
to a grinding surface.

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:52.150
And then you have a provision
for advancing it normal to

00:23:52.150 --> 00:23:54.010
that direction by a
controlled amount.

00:23:54.010 --> 00:23:57.130
If it were not precise, you
would not see sharp edges and

00:23:57.130 --> 00:23:58.200
sharp corners.

00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:02.000
So these are incredibly
expensive.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:05.310
I, therefore, ask it
that you hold them

00:24:05.310 --> 00:24:06.625
tightly with both hands.

00:24:06.625 --> 00:24:08.170
Don't drop them on the floor.

